{{External links|date=November 2013}} {{Infobox University |name = Weill Cornell Graduate School of Medical Sciences <ref>[http://weill.cornell.edu/gradschool/ Homepage - Weill Cornell Graduate School of Medical Sciences in New York City]. Weill.cornell.edu. Retrieved on 2013-09-07.</ref> |image = [[File:Weill_Cornell_Graduate_School_of_Medical_Sciences.png|150px|Cornell University Seal]] |established = 1952 |type = [[Private university|Private]] |city = [[New York City]] |state = [[New York (state)|New York]] |country = [[United States|USA]] |dean = Carl Nathan, MD <ref>[http://weill.cornell.edu/about-us/administrative-officials.html Administrative Officials]. weill.cornell.edu. Retrieved on 2018-02-06.</ref> |faculty = More than 330<ref>[http://weill.cornell.edu/gradschool/faculty/index.html Our Faculty - Weill Cornell Graduate School of Medical Sciences in New York City]. Weill.cornell.edu. Retrieved on 2013-09-07.</ref> |enrollment = More than 400<ref>{{cite web | url = http://dpb.cornell.edu/documents/1000207.pdf | title = Medical Division Total Enrollment | accessdate = 2009-03-20}}</ref> |website = http://gradschool.weill.cornell.edu |image_size=|endowment=}}
[[Image:Cornell med 02.jpg|250px|right|thumb|Weill Medical Center]] The '''Weill Cornell Graduate School of Medical Sciences''' ('''WCGS''') (formerly known as the Cornell University Graduate School of Medical Sciences) is a [[graduate school|graduate]] college of [[Cornell University]] that was founded in 1952 as an academic partnership between two major medical institutions in [[New York City]]: the [[Weill Cornell Medical College]] and the [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center|Sloan Kettering Institute]]. Cornell is involved in the [[Tri-Institutional MD-PhD Program]] with [[Rockefeller University]] and the [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center|Sloan Kettering Institute]]; each of these three institutions is part of a large biomedical center extending along York Avenue between 65th and 72nd Streets on the [[Upper East Side]] of [[Manhattan]].
==Programs of study== Weill Cornell Graduate School of Medical Sciences (WCGS) partners with neighboring institutions along York Avenue, also known as the “corridor of science” in New York City. Such partnerships with [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]], [[NewYork–Presbyterian Hospital|New York-Presbyterian Hospital]], the [[Hospital for Special Surgery]] and [[Rockefeller University|The Rockefeller University]] offer learning.
WCGS offers a variety of programs at both the Masters and Doctoral levels. As a partnership between the Sloan Kettering Institute and Weill Cornell Medical College, WCGS offers seven PhD programs as well as four distinct Masters programs. Additionally, the school offers two Tri-Institutional PhDs, a Tri-Institutional MD/PhD and the opportunity for students to participate in an Accelerated PhD/MBA program. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gradschool.weill.cornell.edu/academics|title=Academics {{!}} Graduate School of Medical Sciences|website=gradschool.weill.cornell.edu|access-date=2016-04-14}}</ref>
PhD Programs: * Biochemistry and Structural Biology * Molecular Biology * Cell and Developmental Biology * Immunology and Microbial Pathogenesis * Pharmacology * Neuroscience * Physiology Biophysics and Systems Biology
Tri-Institutional PhD Programs * Chemical Biology * Computational Biology and Medicine * Tri-I MD / PhD Program
==See also== * [[Weill Cornell Medical College]] * [[Tri-Institutional MD-PhD Program]]
